data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException` catches, or `Thread.ResetAbort`.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely a code-quality improvement — not a migration requirement.
